   The RAP Branch focuses on the development of the
     * Mesoscale Analysis and Prediction System (MAPS), a regional data
       assimilation and forecast system, and the
     * Rapid Update Cycle (RUC), the operational version of MAPS running
       at the National Centers for Environmental Prediction (NCEP).

   The key features of RUC2/MAPS include:
     * high-frequency (every 1 h) 3-d objective analyses over the
       contiguous United States
     * high-frequency short-range model forecasts (out to 12 h) in support
       of aviation and other mesoscale forecast users
     * currently assimilates data from
          + commercial aircraft (relayed primarily through ACARS -
            Aircraft Communications, Addressing, and Reporting System)
          + wind profilers (404 and boundary-layer 915 MHz)
          + rawinsondes
          + surface reporting stations (including some mesonet)
          + buoys
          + RASS (Radio Acoustic Sounding System) - experimental
          + VAD (velocity-azimuth display) winds from NWS WSR-88D radars
          + GOES total precipitable water estimates from Univ. of
            Wisconsin - CIMSS
            And at NCEP
          + SSM/I total precipitable water estimates
          + GOES high-density visible, IR, and water vapor cloud-top cloud
            drift winds
     * uses a hybrid isentropic-sigma vertical coordinate.
     __________________________________________________________________

MAPS/RUC Information and Real-Time Data

     * Verification statistics for 40-km MAPS - updated for 28 May - 15
       September 1997 period
     * Use of GOES precipitable water data every 3 hours. Data from
       CIMSS/Univ. Wisconsin - 11 June 1997 Precipitable water products on
       this page added below.
     * Snow accumulation products from 40-km MAPS now available - 1 Apr
       1997
     * Introduction of snow accumulation and melting with snow cover and
       temperature cycling - 30 Jan 1997
     * Introduction of explicit cloud microphysics in 40-km MAPS with
       cycling of cloud variables - 2 Jan 1997
       Microphysics from NCAR/Penn State MM5 model includes explicit
       forecasts of mixing ratios of cloud water, rain water, snow, ice,
       and graupel, and also a forecast of the number concentration of ice
       particles.

